C1 is a power supply (in this case a battery) decoupling capacitor. While it is
recommended that it's soldered on, it is not required, and the circuit will still operate
To begin, place a component inside of it's right reference by matching the part with
the reference on the table to the right with the reference printed on the PCB, then
solder it to the board. It is recommended to solder all resistors first, then the
ATtiny85/DIP socket, then the transistor, then the LEDs, and finally the 2xAA battery
It is recommended to solder an 8-DIP socket instead of the ATtiny85 on the PCB.
The socket is used to place the ATtiny85 after everything is soldered. A socket makes
it easier to replace the ATtiny85 in case it's boken (for example if the battery is
hooked up backwards). Altough this procedure references the ATtiny85 itself in the
soldering instructions, replacing the ATtiny85 with the 8-DIP socket during
soldering, and installing the ATtiny85 on the soldered socket after soldering will
result in the same functionality, and it is thus recommended.
While the ATtiny85 comes pre-programmed, it is possible to change this firmware to
whatever you would like. This is done thru the TagConnect connector on the tip of
the pumpkin (back side of the PCB). The pinout of the TagConnect is in the circuit's
